<HL> LEISURE &amp; ARTS:
Television: Holiday Specials and Pigskin Bowls
---
By Martha Bayles</HL>
<DD> 12/24/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<TEXT>
   Thursday, Dec. 24, Christmas Eve programs. 
First, 8-9 p.m. EST, on PBS (check local listings): Handel's "Messiah," performed by the Atlanta Symphony under the direction of Robert Shaw. 
Second, 8:30 p.m.-midnight EST, on A&amp;E: Mozart's "The Magic Flute," a 1978 British production with sets designed by David Hockney. 
Third, 9-10 p.m. EST, on PBS: "Carols From King's," traditional music from the King's College, Cambridge, choir. 
Fourth, midnight-1:30 a.m. EST, on NBC: Midnight Mass from St. Peter's in Rome, celebrated by the pope. 

   Saturday, Dec. 26, 8-10 p.m. EST, on HBO (repeated Dec. 28, 30, Jan. 3, 7 and 12): "Into the Homeland." 
Surprisingly, the danger of crypto-Nazis in rural Wyoming has inspired a quite riveting film, starring Powers Boothe as a burnt-out cop looking for his cult-captured daughter. 

   Sunday, Dec. 27, 2-3:30 p.m. EST (or later on stations carrying NFL football), on NBC: "Creole Giselle." 
The Dance Theatre of Harlem's transmutation of the classic ballet based on an Austrian romance to the equally romantic setting of high Creole society in 19th-century Louisiana. 
Bill Cosby hosts this outstanding event, underwritten by AT&amp;T. 

   Sunday, Dec. 27, 9-11 p.m. EST, on CBS: "A Hazard of Hearts." 
Nowadays "romantic" means young lovelies spirited away by inscrutable noblemen to cliff-top mansions with names like Mandrake. 
If this is your cup of tea, catch this first-ever TV version of a Barbara Cartland novel. 

   Monday, Dec. 28, 9-10 p.m. EST, on PBS: "Solti at 75: A Celebration!" 
Sir Georg flies high with the world's top operatic songbirds. 

   Monday, Dec. 28, 9-11 p.m. EST, on NBC: "Roman Holiday." 
This remake of the Oscar-winning 1953 movie stars Catherine Oxenberg as the princess who runs off with a reporter (Tom Conti) and gets trapped by love and a sneaky photographer (Ed Begley Jr.). 

   Wednesday, Dec. 30, 9-11 p.m. EST, on CBS: "The Kennedy Center Honors: A Celebration of the Performing Arts." 
Walter Cronkite tuxes up to host this prestigious tribute to Perry Como, Bette Davis, Sammy Davis Jr., Nathan Milstein and Alwin Nikolais. 
An extra fuss will be made over Irving Berlin. 

   Thursday, Dec. 31, New Year's Eve programs. 
First, 10 p.m.-1 a.m. EST, on PBS: "Happy New Year U.S.A.!" 
From Baltimore, Mel Torme and other pop and jazz greats make hoopla for the musically mature. 
Second, 11 p.m.-2 a.m. EST, on MTV: "New Year's Eve Rock and Roll Ball." 
Hoopla for benighted souls on the younger side. 
Third, 11:30 p.m.-1 a.m. EST, on ABC: "Dick Clark's New Year's Rockin' Eve '88." 
Hoopla for mature rock 'n' rollers with permission to stay out after 1988. 

   Friday, Jan. 1, college football bowl games. 
First, noon-3:30 p.m. EST, on ABC: the Florida Citrus Bowl, Clemson vs. 
Penn State. 
Second, 1:30-4:30 p.m. EST, on NBC: the Sunkist Fiesta Bowl, Nebraska vs. 
Florida State. 
Third, 1:30-5 p.m. EST, on CBS: the Cotton Bowl, Texas A&amp;M vs. 
Notre Dame. 
Fourth, 3:30-7 p.m. EST, on ABC: the USF&amp;G Sugar Bowl, Auburn vs. 
Syracuse. 
Fifth, 4:45-8 p.m. EST, on NBC: the Rose Bowl, Michigan State vs. 
Southern Cal. 
Sixth, 8-11 p.m. EST, on NBC: the Orange Bowl, Oklahoma vs. 
Miami. 

   Friday, Jan. 1, 2:30-4 p.m. EST, on PBS (repeated at 9 p.m.): "From Vienna: The New Year's Celebration 1988." 
On the remote chance that you become weary of football, tune in for the Choir Boys and a once-again tuxed-up Walter Cronkite, rejoicing in Old World style. 

   Friday, Jan. 1, 8 p.m.-midnight EST, on A&amp;E: "Australia Live! 
A Bicentennial Celebration." 
Look on the bright side. 
At least this bunch of celebrities -- Helen Reddy, Paul Hogan, Olivia Newton-John, Ronald Reagan, Margaret Thatcher and Queen Elizabeth II, to name just a few -- are carrying on about something besides the New Year. 

   Friday, Jan. 1, 9-11 p.m. EST, on CBS: "Drop-Out Mother." 
Valerie Harper plays a career woman who decides she has been neglecting her family, and quits in order to become a full-time homemaker. 
Not an easy transition, as it turns out. 

   Tuesday, Jan. 5, 9-10 p.m. EST, on PBS: "Who Lives, Who Dies." 
Once the holidays are over, you can get good and depressed by watching this hard-hitting documentary, funded partly by Ciba-Geigy Corp., focusing on the gross imbalances in America's health-care system. 

